description: From Middle English fracchen (“to make a harsh or strident noise; creak”). Cognate with Scots fratch (“to quarrel”).

entries.meaning: (UK) A dispute, a quarrel; a fight or brawl.

verbs.description: fratch (third-person singular simple present fratches, present participle fratching, simple past and past participle fratched)

entries.meaning: (UK, Yorkshire) To argue, to quarrel; to fight.
